    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1936-08-19T09:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1936-08-19T09:00:00-05:00" n="426"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d426">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">852.00/2685: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Brazil</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gibson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Rio de Janeiro</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-08-19T11:00:00-03:00"
                            >August 19, 1936—11 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received August 19—10:48 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>184. Department’s circular of August 17, 5 p.m. After consultation with the
                    President, the Minister for Foreign Affairs informs <pb facs="0596" n="497"
                        xml:id="pg_497"/> me that he proposes to reply today to the Uruguayan
                    proposal in more or less the following terms: <list>
                        <label>1.</label>
                        <item>An offer of mediation by the American Governments would in fact
                            constitute the recognition of the rebel forces as belligerents and
                            thereby grant them a status which even they have not yet asked
                            for;</item>
                        <label>2.</label>
                        <item>The Civil War in Spain has caused such friction in Europe that an
                            offer of American mediation would appear inopportune, particularly as
                            there would seem to be serious doubts of its success;</item>
                        <label>3.</label>
                        <item>However, if all the countries of the New World accept the idea of
                            mediation in Spain, Brazil will cooperate.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Gibson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
